<DL> <A NAME=9><DT>...pipe. <DD>This 
hints at the old paradox that one is allowed to pray while smoking, 
but not smoke while praying, something occasionally quoted as a 
proof that human thoughts map imperfectly onto formal logic, though 
it probably more indicates the necessity for accounting for temporal 
relations when describing the real world.  (The point of the one-sided 
interdiction is of 
course that one is allowed to pray should one's mind turn to  
Matters Unworldly while smoking, like it did for Bach, but one should not be so 
unconcentrated while praying that one  starts smoking.)</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=142><DT>...Achilles. <DD>We note in passing that it is quite common 
for limericks to be self-referential or make meta-jokes, as in
<P> 
There was a young man from Japan<BR> 
whose verses never would scan.<BR> 
 He said ``Yes, I know<BR> 
 this is really so<BR> 
because I always try to get as many words into the last line as I 
possibly can!''
  <P></A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=143><DT>...record <DD>This reminds me of the guy who tried to slip <em> out</em> of 
a record store with a CD hidden in his trousers.  A hawk-eyed shop 
assistant noted this and politely asked:  
<blockquote> ``Excuse me sir, is that a 
record in your trousers?''<BR> 
``Well, it may not be a record, but I'm mighty 
proud of it!''
</blockquote>
</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=144><DT>...unit. <DD>Someone wanted to write a program that could be
interpreted in this way. I refer to Mel's blackjack program, as described
in [<A HREF="geb.html#Raymond91">Raymond, 1991</A>] as an example of how this has been done.</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=145><DT>...compression. <DD>The
question was put as to how a human could be represented by the presumably
very small amount of data in the human genome. We could compare this with
the  Iterated Functions System [<A HREF="geb.html#Barnsley93">Barnsley and Hurd, 1993</A>] for image compression, in which an
image is stored as a small number of generating functions, which can then
be executed to generate the image with arbitrary precision.</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=146><DT>...time. <DD>Further
upset was caused when <em> prions</em> were found [<A HREF="geb.html#Prusiner84">Prusiner, 1984</A>].  This 
infectious agent is
too small to contain any genetic material and thus has to be protein only,
but a self-replicating protein is forbidden according to .DOGMA I.  The 
current theory [<A HREF="geb.html#Prusiner95">Prusiner, 1995</A>] is that prions are
proteins with an alternative, though less probable, harmful structure, that
can induce other proteins of the same kind to assume the alternate
structure---the remains of .DOGMA I are saved.</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=116><DT>...him. <DD>For those feeling less 
magnanimous and Mock Turtle soup having been mentioned before, here is a recipe for Devil Crab:  Chop a shallot and 8--10 
chive stems.  Fry the shallot in 30 ml butter, add 
200 g of crab meat, 5--10 ml French mustard and 
5 ml Worcestershire sauce.  Let stew on low heat.  Add 
300 ml Bchamel sauce and the chives.  Season with salt and 
cayenne pepper to taste.  Take the stew off the stove and thicken with 
two egg yolks.  Fill dishes with the stew, sprinkle with bread crumbs and 
butter pats.  Bake in oven in 600 K for 180--300 s.</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=120><DT>...Ramanujan <DD>Ramanujan, like many other great mathematicians and
achievers, died young.  There are on the other hand many great mathematicians
and achievers that lived to old age.  I dare not say whether it is dangerous to
be a genius without access to more complete statistics.</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE><A NAME=132><DT>...it. <DD>Thanks to Rene Mandel for
the library lookup.</A>
<PRE><P>
</PRE> </DL>
<BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Kai-Mikael J-Aro <BR>
Tue Feb  6 16:26:27 MET 1996</I>
</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
